results.name: Number of distinct partition numbers dividing n.
link: Giovanni Resta, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000
example: For n = 20 the divisors of 20 are 1, 2, 4, 5, 10, 20 and three of them are also partition numbers: 1, 2, 5, so a(20) = 3.
For n = 42 the divisors of 42 are 1, 2, 3, 6, 7, 14, 21, 42 and five of them are also partition numbers: 1, 2, 3, 7, 42, so a(42) = 5.
mathematica: p = {1}; Table[If[n >= Last@p, AppendTo[p, PartitionsP[1 + Length@p]]]; Length@Select[p, Mod[n, #] == 0 &], {n, 90}] (* _Giovanni Resta_, Jan 22 2014 *)
